description:
World-Renowned Addiction Expert Dr. K reveals the SHOCKING truth about masturbation, pornography, dopamine burnout, incels, and why 60% of men under 30 are single. Dr K from Healthy Gamer! 

Dr. Alok Kanojia (aka Dr. K) is a world-leading addiction expert, Harvard-trained psychiatrist, and founder of Healthy Gamer, the platform helping young adults break free from porn addiction, dopamine burnout, and emotional numbness. He hosts unfiltered mental health conversations on Twitch and is the author of the book, ‘How to Raise a Healthy Gamer’.

He explains:
◽️ The deadly trap that fuels loneliness
◽️ How to rebuild your brain and reclaim your energy from dopamine burnout 
◽️ How social media is hijacking your brain’s reward system
◽️ Why so many young men feel lost and emotionally numb
◽️ How to reconnect with purpose when life feels empty

comments.text:
Ok, I'm glad you asked this question, because I've been listening to this episode over the last 2 days, and I'm presently 1:25:31 into it, and I'm about to shut it off.

The first part, it was good. It was (mostly) on topic. The info about addiction, and even the side tangent that touches on lonely man syndrome, were good. They were relevant to each other and we got to a conclusion. But, THEN, the episode goes on. It spins into new direction after new direction. We're off topic.

It feels like I started a drive intending to go from Boston to DC, but kept taking detours off into New Haven, New York, Jersey City, Cape May, Philly, — but, I'm weary at this point. I'm afraid another detour to Baltimore is coming. But, I really wanted to get to DC.

Now, I don't mean to shame Dr. K here: I have a very "interconnected" mind too. I see the relevance from one tangental topic to another. But, in all my years sitting and talking with people, I have to keep in mind that the listener/the audience does matter. 

And Dr. K begins to get into it around 1:07 where he begins by saying "I used to value credibility over truth." My take away from this part: He's in a place where HIS Truth is what matters to him most. And, I hear that he really doesn't care about how it's being received. If he's being understood. If his message lands at all? He doesn't care. So, ultimately, he also doesn't care about the listener.

And, I want to express some empathy here: I was that person, Dr K. I went through that period. And, in it, upon reflection and asking friends for feedback, I witnessed how much disconnection it sewed with some relationships in my life.  I'm here to share that same feedback with you.

Steven, you are an incredibly strong interviewer. And you seemed utterly lost at times on how to even prompt the next train of thought. At one point you asked "What is the right question to ask you?"

This interview, honestly, is a hot mess for a listener to digest. I think there IS worthwhile information within each topic, but it doesn't fit as a long-form episode. Not this long, anyhow.

Your editors need to cut it into smaller, topical episodes. Too many topics in one episode. People need some coherence.

I don't know, maybe I'll skip ahead to see if Dr. K wraps all the topics up and ties a bow on them that reveal some deeper interconnected truth. But, presently, I need a break.

comments.text: I do love your show.  But this topic of why men are having trouble, no one is talking about the thing that most women I know are talking about.  It is not wanting a man with more money or good looks.  Which of course if you ask a woman her wish list those will be on it. But who are the real guys women date.  Someone who can look after themselves.  Women have done it for years.  We have been brought up in a way there is a good chance you are going to be doing it all with or without a man.  If you have kids there is a good chance you will be raising them alone if you stay married or not.  This is why a lot of women are choosing a different path. Women do not want a grown child to look after.  If a man lives alone does his own cooking and cleaning while holding down a steady job. This is what is attractive. Women have done this for years.  Sure staying fit going for walks getting outside also attractive.  A good conversation and good humor is only found if you get out and talk to people.  How many fellas have actually gone and asked a woman out on a date?  And if she says no ask a different woman.  You need to put yourself out there.  Get out in the real world.  It is also ok to be told no by one woman then go and meet another.  The world does not end if you ask someone out and then have to try again.  Men need to be told it is ok to be single.  It is ok to find your path on your own.  And if you find someone who is like minded walking the same way then maybe ask them on a date.  But finding yourself and your journey first is key.  The other factor is that there are too many people on the planet.  And a lot of woman and men are choosing not to have kids. And that is ok.  The lie of the need for companies to make more money every year is the reason the wealthy want more people born. More people to buy their "stuff" but really the things that we create should be for the demand of the people not the other way around. And if there are less people we need less stuff and that is ok.  The only people that will suffer in this situation are the wealthy that are currently hoarding money.  There is enough food on the planet for everyone and there is enough money being made that if it was distributed effectively everyone would thrive.  But sadly the greed of a few is making it impossible for the many.  The media fills the world with divisive conversations to distract us all from this fact.  But if everyone was fed and living their best life it would be hard to rile them up about any of this nonsense.
